<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-28T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="680" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d680">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 611.419/107</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-28T18:00:00+00:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">December 28, 1914, 6 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>1351. Your 838, December 26 [24?], and 839, December 26, and [819],
                            December 23.<note n="3" xml:id="d680fn1">Nos. 838 and 839 not
                                printed.</note> I have presented same, but I have little hope of
                            success till an answer is received to the proposed working arrangement
                            which the British Government means to cover this and other difficulties
                            caused by embargo.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>